         <ul class="UL1">
            <li ><h3 class="H1">Place Name :</h3> Uluwatu, Bali, Indonesia</li>
            <li><h3 class="H1">Description:</h3>Uluwatu, located on the Bukit Peninsula of Bali, is a legendary surf destination with powerful, peeling left-handers that break over a shallow reef. The wave at Uluwatu is consistent year-round, with the best conditions occurring during the dry season (April to October), when southwesterly swells hit the island’s shores. The main break divides into several sections, including Temples, The Peak, and Racetracks, offering waves that range from playful to challenging.</li>
            <li ><h3 class="H1">What to Expect:</h3> Uluwatu lends itself to intermediate to advanced surfers due to the fast and powerful nature of the waves. However, beginners can still enjoy smaller surf at nearby beaches like Padang Padang. The reef at Uluwatu is sharp, so booties are recommended for those unfamiliar with reef breaks.</li>
            <li><h3 class="H1">Things to Do:</h3> What makes Uluwatu truly special is its amazing scenery. Nestled beneath towering limestone cliffs, the surf spots offer stunning views of the Indian Ocean amid a breathtaking backdrop. After a day of surfing, you can relax at one of the many cliffside cafes and bars, enjoying a spectacular sunset. The area is also home to the iconic Uluwatu Temple, where you can experience a traditional Kecak dance performance. Uluwatu’s combination of world-class surf and cultural richness makes it a must-visit for surfers and travellers alike.</li>
            
         </ul>
